value.0: "I see that you have returned to me. Have you discovered the errors of your ways? Do you realize that you need me now?"
"I do not think it wise that you should travel without companions, but the choice is yours, of course."
"I will follow you gladly, for I owe you much."
"I see we have found the dregs of society."
"The men guarding this place have lost all hope; a good opportunity for us to gain a reputation, yes?"
"That man was passing strange, wouldn't you agree?"
"The difference between wealthy and poor parts of the keep is quickly obvious here."
"Secret passages in our home! It is like playing some elaborate game, yes?"
"I see Alias and the old woman. We should speak to this Momma Dane, since she is such an ardent supporter."
"I do not care for that bard's first song, but his second one was quite interesting."
"These people are very open to diverse forms of worship. I shudder to think what happens at the shrine of fertility in the dead of night."
"That is a man anticipating trouble. I wonder what his story is?"
"The undead do not appear to like each other. We could use this to our advantage."

Comment.value: in Silvertongue manor after meeting Ellysia

value.0: "Looking at her beauty and wealth, I can see why Sir Becket is so anxious to marry the girl."
"The smell of this place turns my stomach. Let us not linger here."

Comment.value: in manticore caves, once the trap is set.

value.0: "Perhaps I should wait outside this room, so that no one gets caught in the trap."
"Such a disreputable shop. I do not feel comfortable in here."
"There is the home of the mage. We should go and see her."
"Leading stupid beasts around? This is not a noble task for such as us."
"We could use these explosives to block the tunnels, unless you plan on killing all the duergar yourself."
"So this is the place where justice could rule. I could get used to this."
"I expected greater displays of wealth from Sir Becket."
"I am sorry. Did you wish to speak to me, my friend?"
"I do not think it wise that we should part. There is much danger here and you might need someone to watch your back."
"What a lovely decision. I do hope you don't return to find me murdered or eaten or anything."
"Very well. I think I shall go and speak with Yenna in her tower. I think there is much I could learn from her."
"And how would you have me behave now?"
"Why would you want to bring a wizard along in your group if you do not want them to cast spells. This is utter foolishness."
"It would be foolish of me not to cast combat spells. I am tough in a fight, but not as powerful as a well timed spell."
"That is a plan I can heartily agree with."
"I do not think I shall be of much assistance there."
"As you wish."
"I will move as silently as I know how."
"I shall do as you say. I was not very good at it anyway."
"Though it is not my specialty, I will do what I can."
"As you wish. How far would you have me stand?"
"As you have stated, so shall it be done."
"I will do as you say. I can spot an enemy as quickly as anyone."
"That is fine, though I think I could discern an enemy as quickly as you could."
"I would think I am capable of doing so on my own, but if you have suggestions... I can allow that."
"I will use my extensive knowledge to see if I can identify anything you have."
"I see. What manner of buffing spells would you have me use?"
"And what is my target?"
"So be it!"
"What shall I cast, then?"
"I can do that. Are you certain?"
"And what is my target?"
"Was there anything else then, friend?"
"So be it!"
"Oh course, my friend. What can Jaboli bring her wisdom to bear on?"
"Would you like anything else, my friend?"
"I must have slept wrong last time we rested. I can't get my hair to lay down at all."
"Do you want anything else?"
"My neck is a little sore. I could use a good massage, but now is not the time for such things."
"I was just contemplating the meaning of life. I think I just about had an answer, but now it is gone. Thanks. I'm just kidding, my friend!"
"I feel like a goddess... I am that wonderful!"
"I would be better if we would not get killed again. Do try to watch what you are doing."
"I think I swallowed a morsel that does not agree with me. Wait... <StartAction>[Belch]</Start> ah, that is better."
"I am not so delicate that I need you to worry about me constantly."
"I can use my other senses to stop from bumping into walls, but it is hard to cast spells at an opponent you cannot see."
"I have had worse wounds from playful wrestling with my siblings. Do not worry so much about me."
"I have taken some serious wounds, but I shall live. We might want to rest a bit soon."
"I have been gravely wounded. I request a brief stop soon, that I might recover from these injuries."
"I can feel a poison flowing through my veins. We need to find an antidote before it cripples me."
"I seem to have contracted some kind of disease. I will survive for a while, but we should seek a cure as soon as we can."
"I would stay and advise you, if you would be interested in listening to my advice. I have always wanted to be involved in politics, without being the leader."

Comment.value: If the PC lost the election

value.0: "I have no real plans. I might go out on my own and see what the world has to offer me. Who knows, maybe someone will want me to become their advisor."
"It is also possible that you will somehow still achieve your dream and become the ruler of the keep, though I know not how. Somehow, this just doesn't feel like it is over."
"I have no real plans. I might go out on my own and see what the world has to offer me. Who knows? Maybe someone will want me to become their advisor."

"The truth is, I have no idea. I thought you would make a good leader, yet recent events have shown me otherwise. I am sorry. I do hope you can achieve your dreams, but I do not think I will be a part of them."

Comment.value: if pc has not done the election yet

value.0: "I would stay with you, if you would have me. Perhaps, if you win the election, you could make me your Banner. I have always wanted to be involved in politics, without being the leader."
"I want to see what a good leader with good advisors can accomplish. I think it is possible that you could usher in a new era of growth and peace for these lands, given enough time and resources."
"I would also be good at the role of judge for your people, I think. It is something that holds great interest for me. As your Banner, I could serve such a function."
"If you die and do not return to life? I would leave here. I do not care for leadership myself and I know no one who would make a better leader than you."
"You have a confidence that makes people trust you. You are not evil. Your motives are not always apparent, but you have proven you can hold your own, even in difficult situations."
"I did not like the way you treated the Gelani/Thaddeus situation, but everyone makes mistakes. I know in your heart you are not evil. And you are undeniably capable of accomplishing your goals."

Comment.value: if pc got feran and ellysia together again

value.0: "The way you handled Feran and Ellysia was like a poet who carefully chooses which words to use and which to discard to gain the greatest beauty."
"That alone was enough to show me that you have the true heart of a good leader."
"Politics is entirely about motivation and discernment. I should think that by now you would realize that these are exactly the skills that I have."
"If you are willing to trust me and listen to my advice, most of the time, then yes, I will do my best to help you become one of the best rulers this world has ever known."
"I already think you would be a good ruler, or I would not have made such an offer. Still, I think any good ruler knows that they need to surround themselves with people who will give good advice."
"I would not have made the suggestion, if I did not want to know."
"I would not expect you to do so. A good ruler has advisors to advise <him/her>, not to make <his/her> decisions. I advise, you listen, then decide for yourself. That is wise discernment."
"I am pleased to hear you say so. For a non-rakshasa you have amazing discernment."
"I would not have expected such from you, but it is true. I never expected such a meeting of the minds in this realm... what a strange thing."
"You have proven this time and time again. I never expected such a meeting of the minds in this realm... what a strange thing."
"That is what I feared. So be it, I shall find something else to do when this is over. Perhaps I might travel to some place far from here. A journey by ship over the eastern sea might be pleasant."
"I do not know what has made you so hostile, but I do not like it. Perhaps you would prefer that I leave right now? You can finish this on your own."

Comment.value: Jaboli goes to Yenna's tower, where she will wait for the PC. Set to the fired starting condition.

value.0: Jaboli snarls, then stalks off.
"If you want to be treated with respect, then treat others with respect. Your mocking of me cannot be tolerated for long. Do better, or I shall leave you to do this on your own."
"There is more to this world than your foolish scholars and priests know. Just because no one has ever returned successfully from such a voyage does not mean it cannot be done."
"We should get going again. There is much to be done."
"When my people banished me, I was told in no uncertain terms that to return would mean death. No, I do not foresee a time when I am eager to see others of my kind again."
She shrugs. "I suppose." She sighs in painful reminiscence and turns away.
"I didn't think of it as a rebellion. Not at first, though that is certainly where it led."
"Yes. I killed many of my own kind."
"It started innocently enough. I simply began to talk to other young, wealthy rakshasa. I would feel out which ones might be sympathetic to my point of view and get them to attend meetings."
"It started innocently enough. I simply began to talk to other young, wealthy rakshasa. I would feel out which ones might be sympathetic to my point of view and get them to attend meetings."
"We weren't doing anything wrong, but our ideas were subversive. One night we had about thirty rakshasa and a hundred slaves."
"It is a lot of rakshasa, but slaves are very numerous in our home. It was the inclusion of the slaves that began the slaughter though. That was my first mistake."
"It was the inclusion of the slaves that began the slaughter though. That was my first mistake."
"Apparently the slaves had been spreading the word that there were rakshasa willing to stand up and fight for them. They secretly prepared and when we had our meeting that night..."
"They never stood a chance. Hundreds of thousands of slaves were killed that night. A few hundred of my people were killed, but the rebellion was put to an end. Brutally."
"That I was. I even thought that things might change after the rebellion. I thought my people would see what despair they had wrought."
"They took one look at the rebelling slaves and the burning city and they turned on them and began to slaughter them as quickly as they could"
"They had no interest in watching their precious society fall completely, and neither did I. We did not wish to be ruled by those we had enslaved."
"Our skins have magical protection, so that only weapons of powerful magic can do any damage to us. The slaves had clubs and knives."
"The slaves were tortured until my people had the names of all rakshasa who ever attended our meetings."
"They gathered us up and allowed us to give ourselves into the military, to help recover our lost slave population, or choose an honorable death. I was not so lucky."
"Every single one of my companions joined the military. I gave what I thought was a rousing speech, but even before I could finish, my words were hidden by the hissing of my old friends."
"Idealistic... foolish... all of the things we are when we are young. Some of us, at least."
"They beat me, tortured me, stripped me of most of my power and exiled me from my home. There is more honor in death than in exile."
She sighs. "We had best get moving. There are important things for us to do still."
"Yes. They beat me, tortured me, stripped me of most of my power and exiled me from my home. There is more honor in death than in exile."
"I awoke on this plane, and it took all of my willpower to stand up and begin my life again."
"Trip doesn't like meetings. Too many smelly people gathered in a hot, stinky room, stepping on my tail... a horrible idea in the first place."
"I am trying to tell my story, Trip. Try not to interrupt."
"When you have little reason to live, you do not fear death. I imagine the slaves felt pretty desperate."
"A slave is a terrible warrior, but when you have nothing worth living for, you will do almost anything to be free."

"You would not have enjoyed living there, I can tell you. Only the most beautiful of slaves had any pleasure in their lives. I fear you would have been sent to the mines, like the majority of slaves."
"I do not say these things to offend you. But so much of life as a rakshasa is wrapped up in our slave culture."
"Yes, that is one of the festering wounds caused by the repugnant institution of slavery. I did not realize how detrimental to our society it was."
"My people have many problems, it is true. We also have some very noble qualities, twisted as we have become. I did not realize how detrimental to our society slavery was."
"I had no problem with slavery until I lived here amongst societies made up of entirely free peoples. At the time I did not realize how detrimental to our society it was."
"No, though I have grown to believe that slavery is a repugnant institution, I did not realize how detrimental to our society it was."
"I lived in a beautiful mansion, surrounded by the fairest slaves of many races. My every whim was fulfilled, almost instantly."
"The problem with having everything is that life quickly grows boring. I decided, to make life more interesting, I would go out to explore other realms."
"You wouldn't understand, unless you have experienced similar situations. Let us just say that my parents were quite happy to have me joining their 'exploratory expedition', as it was called."
"We found a new people, a fascinating realm full of scholars, artists and philosophers. They were not a fierce, warlike people, which made them easy to conquer."
"There was one hold out. One small group of scholars who were resisting us from inside their largest library. It was the size of a small city and contained a copy of every writing ever found."
"Do not ask me to tell about myself if you will not hear my tale as I would tell it."
"Finally, the leader of our expedition made a deal with the warring scholars. He agreed to preserve every single page of writing, if the scholars would give up peacefully."
"The scholars agreed and were horrified when our men took each book and scroll and ripped them apart, shuffling all the pages together into one giant, undecipherable mess."

"Watching the tears of the scholars, not from the chains on their necks, but from the destruction of their knowledge, I became sickened by the 'honor' of my people. But that is enough for now. Let us continue."
"No, they were quite happy to have me joining their 'exploratory expedition', as it was called, though it turned out to be little more than a conquering force."
"No, that was much later in life. I joined one of our 'exploratory expeditions', as they were called, though it turned out to be little more than a conquering force."
"You would have made a lovely slave there. My people like their slaves to be examples of great beauty from the races they have conquered."
"I see that you have returned to me. Have you discovered the errors of your ways? Do you realize that you need me now?"
"I see that you have returned to me. Have you discovered the errors of your ways? Do you realize that you need me now?"
"Leave me be, then. I am studying with Yenna. I have learned a lot already. Soon I shall be ready to journey off on my own."
"It seems to me that you are the one with a poor attitude. You mistreated me; cast me off like unwanted debris. Why should I come with you now?"
"I have not been paid! I do not see any reason for me to treat this as a professional choice! If it is a job, then you already fired me. If you rescind your decision to fire me... I QUIT!"
"I suppose that is the only argument that could compel me to follow you again. Very well, let us be off."
"I will do so, but mind that you treat me with the same respect that you would be treated with."
"If you could pause for just a moment, I would like to speak to you, my friend."
"As you wish. I will allow you to fumble about on your own without any advice from friends."
"Look at my fingernails; they are filthy! I was hoping you might give me a manicure. Of course it is important!"
"And here I thought you would like to discuss the latest dress-styles in this border town. How silly of me."
"I always judge whether my words are important enough to present your royal ears; you should know that by now."
"I always stop you so that I can discuss trivialities. I probably just wanted to know if my hair was ruffled, but now you have ruined the moment!"
"Do you think I would ask you to stop if all I wanted to know was if this outfit made me look fat? I don't think so."
"No. I enjoy watching you fumble about on your own. I can hold my advice to myself."

Comment.value:
After Election
if pc has been nice to Jab, she will do this instead of her betrayal line.

value.0: "<FirstName>, I wanted to tell you that I have made up my mind. I would like to offer you the honor of being my Rakathi, my <brother/sister>."
Her eyes harden and her hair stands on end. "How dare you insult me after I have tried to offer you the greatest honor my people can bestow."
"You can finish this quest on your own. I want nothing more to do with you!"
"I have a bonding present for you, Rakathi. I have given some of my own energy to create this amulet. I hope that you will wear it proudly."
Jaboli stands shocked."I... I am sorry if I have misled you, <FirstName>. I love you too, but only as a <brother/sister>!"
"No, it isn't. You forget that I can read a lie quite easily."
"There is nothing we can do about this situation now, but someday we will have to resolve it. For now, we should be going."
Jaboli stares into your eyes. "Good. I guess we should continue then. Sorry for the misunderstanding."
"As are you, <FirstName>. We should be going now. I am proud of you, my Rakathi!"
"It is one of the greatest honors one of my people can bestow, and, to my knowledge, it has never been bestowed on a non-rakshasa before."

Comment.value: if PC helped the two lovers be rejoined.

value.0: "What you did in bringing those two together... it is nothing short of miraculous! Somewhere inside you there is a romantic spirit. You showed him a justice I would not have expected."
"Every time I think I understand you better, you do something to annoy me and destroy my respect. Have it your way then. But I know you are hiding a romantic soul. Deeply hidden."
"That or he'll regret that he ever opened his mouth to you. Well, I just wanted you to know that I was impressed."
She laughs, merrily. "You could be right about that, but maybe it will turn out better than we expect. I just wanted you to know that I am impressed."
"I agree. I never took you for such a soft heart, but I am impressed. I just wanted you to know that."
"I think we need to speak about your actions in regards to Gelani and Thaddeus."

Comment.value:
if Gelani is head of merchant guild
increase Jaboli liking PC

value.0: "Your actions were very honorable. You restored the faith of one who had no hope and in doing so you earned the trust of not only Gelani, but also of many others in the keep."
"I do not feel as though I say it enough, but it is at times like this when I deeply respect you as a friend. I have not decided yet, but I am thinking I would like to call you my Rakathi."
"That means <brother/sister> in my native tongue. It is an honor that is rarely given, and never to one who is not a rakshasa. But if your actions continue to be honorable, you will be the first."
"I see that I was mistaken. Perhaps, you are undeserving of such a title then."
"Ha! You can keep dreaming. It does involve a bonding gift; however, I have not decided what it will be."
"I am glad you see it that way. I always worry how others will comprehend my foreign ways, but with you, it is like speaking to a close sibling."
"That is all I wanted to say. We should carry on."

Comment.value:
if Thaddeus supported and Gelani assassinated
decrease Jaboli likes PC

value.0: "Your actions were cruel, cold, and despicable. You acted without judging the merits of the situation, and for that I feel as though I should condemn you!"
"Tell me, why should I remain with you? Why should I continue to help one such as you? You are every bit as bad as my own, corrupt peoples."
"Then I shall go. If you come to your senses and realize how much you need me, you shall find me in Yenna's tower. Maybe I can learn something useful from her."
"Of course you need me! Look at all the trouble you have caused already, and I was with you."
"Very well, I shall stay with you for now. But I shall be watching you carefully and judging your actions. I trust you shall stick to a more honorable code in the future."
"There are always options. You just figured you could make some easy gold by preying on the innocent."
"I can judge you on all your actions and all of the things you have done including this one, and it does not look so good from where I sit!"
"You cannot claim to be saving lives when you kill an innocent such as Gelani. She had done nothing to deserve this fate!"

Comment.value: trigger just outside Yenna's tower, just after PC has spoken to Yenna and knows about Garrot

value.0: "This is a perplexing situation. Yenna is a very powerful mage, yet she is bound by someone who is obviously more powerful."
"I don't mean frightening, although it is that too. I just wonder why she would choose to let us know about this person."
"If this other person is more powerful than her, why would she risk telling us anything? If she isn't really afraid of this person, then why not do battle herself?"
"I just don't think that I fully understand her motives. I need to work this out. I think it could be important."
"It might be more pressing than that. She said that you had the blood of an outsider. That would suggest to me that your lineage is possibly connected to some kind of demon or devil."
"I am not sure what to think. But follow my logic here and see if it makes sense to you. It is obvious that this creature has taken an interest in you and knows your background."
"It also knew that you would come here. Mages often call upon outsiders for information, so the creature you face might also be an outsider."
"Such a creature would have powers possibly beyond that of Yenna. Such a creature would also be capable of controlling an army. Do you see where I am going with this?"
"We know that there is an illithid involved. This does not mean that there is no one else involved."
"It is more than that. I think he is controlling his forces and spending time here in the keep."
"I... I need more time to think about this. But you should be wary. Anyone you are talking to in the keep might actually be an enemy."
"That is good. I am glad you will heed my advice."
"I am not the type who is usually paranoid. I will keep thinking on this and watching those to whom we speak."
"I don't think <FirstName> could possibly be a demon or a devil. I just can't imagine it."
"I do not find your imagination, nor your ability to think to be an overwhelming talent. Mind your own business." She turns away from Kaidala, dismissing her entirely.
"You know that I too am an outsider, if the wizards are to be believed. But I don't think the <lad/lass> looks much like an azer."
"You think <master/mistress> might be a demon? Trip finds this to be most exciting!"
"I am not sure. She said that you had the blood of an outsider. That would suggest to me that your lineage is possibly connected to some kind of demon or devil."
"If my conjectures do not interest you, then I shall quit them entirely. Do not make the mistake of believing I am without feelings. Your insults are remembered."

Comment.value: if PC did buy the home

value.0: "I think you made a wise decision in purchasing it. I am thinking that it could contain some fine treasure in it. Maybe even some gear to make up for the loss of ours."
"I thought that might spark some interest in you. There are other reasons to do it, as well."
"I know, but that is only one of the reasons why I think it is a good idea."
"It shows that you are seriously committed to the people of the keep. You would only purchase an expensive piece of property if you plan on staying."
"It also proves that you have the courage to face an enemy head on. Since no one here was willing to drive out the haunting spirits, it will encourage your followers and intimidate your opponents."
"It is important that everyone knows you are serious in your commitment to the keep. Besides... you never know what will happen."
"Yes. I am excited to see what we may find in our new home."
"I was there when you earned that gold. We are a party and we share the gold, remember? It is *our* purchase. Get used to the idea."
"It is just a hunch I have. I cannot explain it any better than that, but I feel like it is a good thing that we own this house."
"I was there when you earned that gold. We are a party and we share the gold, remember? It is *our* purchase. Get used to the idea."

value.0: "I find I am still shaken from the suddenness of our deaths and our return to life. I am pleased that I am not dead, but I wonder what the price might be for our lives?"
"I think we should watch what happens and see how much this power expects to guide our actions. If we test the limits, we might find out how much control it really has."
"Do not push too hard, but when we are being guided, perhaps try to make a choice that is not obvious. Until we are in a specific situation, I cannot say exactly."
"I will try to suggest something when I have the opportunity. Until then, we should be going."
"I think you should take this more seriously. This thing has a power to bring us back to life. It might also have the power to suddenly kill us."

LinkComment.value: if PC has heard Trip's story about Undercity

value.0: "You do not tell me what to do anymore! I am tired of hearing you bark commands and treat others as though they were cattle for you to chew upon! I am leaving!"
"I have been thinking and I have decided that I can no longer work with you. Your actions have proven that you care nothing for me. You are evil, <FirstName>!"
"The voice is right. It is clear to me now that you have no intention of changing your ways or working towards making a stable, lawful society."
"You are everything that I fought against on my home plane and I will not submit to your tyranny anymore than I submitted to theirs!"
"What good to protect them from the Masked Man's army if it means leaving them under your cruel thumb! You are an evil despot and I should never have helped you become their leader!"
"That... that is true. You did choose me as Banner, so perhaps you will be willing to listen to reason and serve justice."
<StartCheck>[Failed]</Start> "Even now you try to impose your tyrannical control over me! I am gone, and you cannot stop me!"
<StartCheck>[Failed]</Start> "There is no evidence of change from where I am standing. I can no longer assist you in this endeavor."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "There has been little evidence of change from where I stand. Still, to listen to the Masked Man's voice would be foolish. We must destroy it, and soon."
<StartCheck>[Failed]</Start> "I am not heeding the voice. He is simply telling me things I already knew. I can no longer assist you in this endeavor."
"I will leave you... leave here... and try to find a place where I can use my powers to improve people's lives, rather than destroy them!"
"As if I would fall trembling to your threats! I have faced foes more fearsome than you! I leave you here, coward!"
"Is it possible? Have you actually learned something about honor, that you would let me go when you need me the most?"
"It is too late for such pleas! I am no longer yours to command. I leave you here."
"I thought your mind was strong, lass. The Masked Man's voice speaks to me too, but he is easy to resist. He is our enemy. Don't let him weaken you."
"<FirstName> has many flaws, Jaboli. If you leave now, how can we ever teach <him/her> the path <he/she> must follow?"
"Trip can hear the Masked Man's voice too, Jaboli. He tries to trick your mind! You must fight him!"

<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "The voice is... is our enemy, the Masked Man. He is preying on my fears. But what I have stated is still the truth. You are not to be trusted! Still, I must finish this enemy."
"Oh, <FirstName>! I worry so much about you and the path you have chosen. But I shall stay by your side, at least until the Masked Man is truly dead and the people of the keep are safe."
"Let us go, and teach this creature a lesson. Our purpose is set. Let none cross us now!"
"Once again I am beholden to you and your magic weapon for my life. I worry what the final cost might entail... Shall we be on our way again?"
"I shall watch your back for you. I fear our enemy has spies everywhere."
"Be careful. I fear our enemy might have spies everywhere we go. You should have someone watching your back."
"I am afraid my services have already been reserved. Please leave me be."
"We must never give up... never give in... never be less than the best we can be."
"Trip, why are you shaking so? Is something wrong?"
"Trip was just remembering what it was like being dead. I don't like dying much."
"Nobody likes dying much. It's not as if it is a whole lot of fun."
"Trip knows that, it is just that Trip is so used to hiding in the shadows and feeling safe there, but when I died the shadows frightened me."
"You were familiar with something and now it frightens you. This has translated into a fear of shadows in life too?"
"You are so smart Jaboli! That is exactly it. How can Trip make it better?"
"How should I know? I discerned the problem; that doesn't mean I know how to solve it."
"But... but... you are the smartest one. There must be some way for Trip to feel safe in the shadows again!"
"Uh, sure you are, <master/mistress>, but... um... Trip did not want to bother you with petty problems. That why I went to Jaboli... yes, that's why!"
"Poor Trip. I do not mean to be such a coward, <master/mistress>. Maybe when you died everything was bright and cheery?"
"I guess I can try to think of something. Hmm, you like dirt, right?"
"Yes, dirt is very nice. Trip likes to take his food and rub it in the dirt real good and then chew the dirt with its gritty, yummy taste."
"So imagine that the shadows are just dirt that you can hide in. Like you are rolling in the dirty light."
"You mean like a corpse hides in the dirty ground?"
"No, that's not what I'm mean..."
"That is genius! Trip is in awe of Jaboli. I love finding corpses in the ground, like some really tricky game of hide and seek! Now Trip can play it too."
"Uh... glad I could help." Jaboli shakes her head in disgust.
"Dirty light! Genius!"
"Now where is that... I thought I had it right here? It must be... TRIP, GET OVER HERE RIGHT NOW AND GIVE IT BACK!"
"What are you yowling about, Jaboli? What did Trip do wrong?"
"You know what you did, now give it back!"
"Trip has no idea what you are talking about. Trip would never steal something from a friend."
"If I have to ask you one more time, you will be on tonight's menu."
"Oh, ha, ha, you mean this little thing? I thought you had thrown it away. I didn't want you to litter so I picked it up."
"Don't you ever touch my things again!"
"Of course not, Jaboli. Trip is sorry."
"I guess I can overlook it this time."
"Jaboli? Would you really eat Trip?"
"You're a little scrawny, but with some fattening up, you might taste all right." Jaboli eyes him slowly.
"Eek!"
"I have been thinking, Kaidala. There is little reason for us to fight. We can both work together and we both want different things out of life. We should try to get along."
"I guess you're right. It's not as if we are in a competition. Actually, I've never really figured out what you want out of life."
"That is because you are not as intuitive when it comes to understanding other people's motivations and desires."
"Oh, yes, we're going to get along really well, as long as you keep the humility flowing. If you are so good at this, what do you think I want out of life?"
"And here I thought you might actually hand me a challenge. You are too simple to read. You want <FirstName>, of course."
"Don't... don't be ridiculous. That's... that's impossible. Why... why would you say such a thing?"
"You can try to hold your emotions in however you want, but they are there in every glance, in every touch, in every moment you share with <him/her>."
"You don't know what you are talking about!"
"That is fine. You keep yourself in a state of denial. As long as you have something to be passionate about, perhaps you won't whine about seeking death so much."
"Why don't you just shut up?"
"I guess we won't be getting along so well after all."
"I guess not."

value.0: Kaidala blushes. "Oh... I guess I have been a little obvious about that. But there are other things I want out of life. Why don't you name a few?"
"All of your ambitions in life are now focused around <FirstName>. Even your dream of going back and restoring your forest is permeated with visions of you and <him/her>. It is rather pathetic."
"Pathetic? Because I want to live in my home with the one I love? Some people would call it romantic. People with real emotions!"
"It is pathetic that your every dream would collapse and you would lose your entire will to live if <he/she> died. What <FirstName> really needs is someone strong and independent."
"Do you think that when <he/she> is trying to rule an empire, that there will be time for <him/her> to cater to your every need? You need to grow some backbone, child."
"Are you suggesting that <FirstName> would be better off with you?"
"No!"
"This is our fight. Don't get in the way."
"I have no interest in such things. But, yes, <he/she> would be better off with someone like me, who can think independently and survive without constant attention."
"Ha! I have no interest in such things. But, yes, <he/she> would be better off with someone like me, who can think independently and survive without constant attention."
"I can do just fine without constant attention. Besides, two rulers are better than one. I will be there to support <him/her>, as <his/her> friend, if nothing else."
"What a valuable resource to have sitting by your side. An emotionally crippled nymph."
"Kaidala, I wish to speak to you about something, but it is a delicate subject. I fear you are going to feel insulted."
"Go ahead, Jaboli. I doubt you could say anything bad about me that I haven't already thought about myself."
"You don't know my people very well. We can insult people as quickly as we can say hello. But what I have to say... it is a request."
"Spit it out or hold it to yourself. Just make up your mind."
"It is just that I grow tired of your wallowing in self-pity. Yes, you have lost some of your physical beauty. Yes, you have been scarred by your past. But get over it! Get on with life!"
"What?!? You have no idea what I feel like! How dare you judge my attitude and my actions? You are so confident about everything, you obviously don't know what real pain is like!"
"I don't know pain? My own people despise me! I was stripped of my most powerful magic, of my wealth and privilege, of my true love, and sent here to begin everything again!"
"I face suspicious looks and outright hatred by the people of this world and I desperately miss... it doesn't matter."
"My point is that we have both suffered tragedy, yet you seem so trapped inside your pain that you don't see all that is good in your life."
The women glare at you, then at each other. Finally, they drop their gaze and ignore each other.
"What have I done to face your scorn, Jaboli? I still fight to help you. Even as the pain in my face still scorches me, I struggle on. If I am a little depressed, have I not earned it?"

"You take her side in this? What have I done to face such scorn? I still fight to help you. Even as the pain in my face still scorches me, I struggle on. If I am a little depressed, have I not earned it?"
"We have both earned the right to give up and just lay down and die. I don't ask you to forget the pain that you suffer, merely to learn to cope with it without... whining so much."
"Whining?!?"
"And if you could stop with the shrill shrieking too, that would be good."
Kaidala stares at Jaboli furiously, but refuses to make any retort.
"See. That's already an improvement." Jaboli smiles wickedly and turns away from Kaidala.
"Calibast, you seemed to have a rough dream last time we rested. Would you care to talk about it?"
"Was I that restless?"
"You woke me out of a dead sleep. I could hardly focus on memorizing my spells the next day."

"Sorry about that, lass. It was a strange dream. I had killed a man and was fleeing from justice. I had a really good reason for killing him, but whenever I went to tell my side of the story, I froze up."
"That is a disturbing dream. Does it mean anything to you? Maybe something from your past?"
"Somedays your discernment is downright chilling, Jaboli. I am thinking it is something from my past. When I was young, my father and I got into an argument."
"I told him I wished he was dead and stormed off in a rage. He died the next day when an angry slave, an earth elemental, got loose and caught my father off-guard."
"So you blamed yourself for the accident. You do know it was not your fault, do you not?"
Both of your companions glare at you, then shrug and turn away. "Very well, we should continue."
"I know that! I didn't say it was. I just thought it might be connected to my dream."
"There was something else that helped you make that connection, perhaps?"

"Just before I awoke, I was attacked by a large earth elemental. The thing laughed at me and said 'I killed your father for you, just like you wanted. Now it's time for you to pay up.' I figure that says it all."
"That is... unusual. I would say that your guilt is not resolved yet. You need to deal with it soon though. These inner torments could be the cause for your erratic behavior towards yourself."
"Don't hurt your brain or anything. It was just a dream. I have plenty to feel guilty about. My father is a long, distant hurt."
Calibast gives you a glare, then begins to laugh.
"We are both here for you."
"All right, enough sentimentality. Let's get some work done. I feel the need to kill something soon. Oh, and... thank you. Both of you."
"<FirstName>, you should know better than that."
"No, he is right. There was something else that connects the dream to my past."
"Calibast? Would you mind if I ask you a question?"
"Of course not, Jaboli. I always have time for a pretty lass. What is on your mind?"
"You spend so much time and effort on carousing with women and drinking, yet you do not seem to ever be pleased with yourself after the fact."
"That's not a question, lass. It's more of an accusation. Besides, are you jealous?"
"Hardly jealous and don't try to change the subject. <FirstName>, do you not think the behavior of our companion is odd?"
"Sorry, I didn't realize it had gone so far. I saw that you both had feelings for each other, but... well, never mind. Not my business."
"Tame me? What is that supposed to mean... ah, never mind!" It is an unusual sight to see an azer blush.
"It doesn't truly bother me one way or another, but it bothers <him/her>. That was my point. Why act in a way that disgusts you so much?"
"You see Jaboli, there is nothing odd about my behavior. Besides, I don't have to justify myself to you."
"I wasn't asking for justification. I was just wondering why you continue to act that way, when your own behavior disgusts you?"
"I... I can't... I don't..." He throws his hands up in disgust. "Women!"
"You can avoid the question for now, but someday you will have to face whatever has you so troubled that you fear commitment more than death."
"Not yet. I will come back for you."
"Yes. Please follow me."
"Never mind."
"I think we need to part ways."
"No, never mind."
"Wait here until I return."
"I need to go."
